    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nAfter #35988, `vim.treesitter.get_string_parser()` opens a buffer under the hood in order to allow the underlying `LanguageTree` object to have a unified codepath tracking injections via extmarks. But that can be slow and litter hundreds of unlisted buffers in some situations.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`get_string_parser` should be a (substantially) streamlined \"fast path\" (for tree-sitter, _all_ parsers are string parsers!) for\n1. static/immutable\n2. one-shot\n3. single-language (i.e., no injections, period!)\n\nparsing; everything else should be punted to the (default) buffer parser, if necessary for a scratch buffer that downstream users are expected to handle themselves (e.g., reuse or burn in a fire, whatever works best for their specific case). The function should return a static parsed `LanguageTree` and then clean up after itself.\n\nIn contrast, the default `get_parser` codepath should work directly on buffers via #34008.\n\nStretch goals: \n1. convenience API for handling scratch buffers?\n2. `vim.hl.string(str)` that either runs a (one-shot) highlighter on the string parser or simply runs a highlight query and then iterates over the captures itself (DRY, but performance may be worth it?)",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
